HOW TO RESIZE EFI PARTITION
===========================

0. original source https://superuser.com/a/1289122

1. Create unallocated disk space
2. View disk information


  lsblk -f

3. Check FAT32/VFAT for EFI
4. Check if EFI are already mounted on /boot or /boot/efi


  ls /boot
  ls /boot/efi

  mount EFI if not mounted

  mount /dev/nvme0n1p1 /boot/efi

5. Backup EFI content


  mkdir $HOME/efi-bak
  rsync -av /boot/efi/ $HOME/efi-bak

6. Delete and recreate EFI


  sudo gdisk /dev/nvme0n1

  list partition

  p

  notice that every listed entry has ordered first and last sector
  if you see an unordered, that is your unallocated disk space, take note
  ensure EFI partition number, should be 1

  delete partition

  d
  <select_EFI_partition_number>

  create new partition

  n

  select partition number

  Enter to use default
  should be 1

  select first sector

  Enter to use default
  check if the sector location are matching with the unallocated

  select last sector

  Enter to use default
  check if the sector location are matching with the unallocated

  enter code for partition

  EF00

  write changes and exit

  w

7. Format EFI partition


  partprobe /dev/nvme0n1
  mkfs.fat -F32 /dev/nvme0n1p1

8. Restore EFI content


  mount /dev/nvme0n1p1 /boot/efi
  rsync -av $HOME/efi-bak/ /boot/efi

9. Update fstab


  blkid | grep EFI
  vim /etc/fstab

  replace the UUID

  UUID=XXXX-XXXX /boot vfat umask=0077 0 2

10. Update grub


  sudo grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg
